SKILL|node-inspect-debugger|"Debug Node.js via --inspect + Chrome DevTools Protocol CLI."
STEP|1|**`node inspect`** — built-in, zero install, CLI REPL. Best for quick poking.
STEP|2|**`ndb` / CDP via `chrome-remote-interface`** — scriptable from Node/Python; best when you want to automate many breakpoints, collect state across runs, or debug non-interactively from an agent loop.
STEP|3|Prefer `node inspect` first.** It's always available and the REPL is fast.
STEP|4|A Node test fails and you need to see intermediate state
STEP|5|ui-tui crashes or behaves wrong and you want to inspect React/Ink state pre-render
STEP|6|tui_gateway child processes (`_SlashWorker`, PTY bridge workers) misbehave
STEP|7|You need to inspect a value in a closure that `console.log` can't reach without patching
STEP|8|Perf: attach to a running process to capture a CPU profile or heap snapshot
STEP|9|Don't use for:** things `console.log` solves in under a minute. Breakpoint-driven debugging is heavier; use it when the payoff is real.
STEP|10|In the `repl` sub-mode:** type any JS expression, including access to locals/closure variables. `Ctrl+C` exits back to `debug>`.
STEP|11|**Wrong line numbers in TS source.** Breakpoints hit the emitted JS, not the `.ts`. Either (a) break in the built `dist/*.js`, or (b) enable sourcemaps (`node --enable-source-maps`) and use `sb('src/a
STEP|12|**`--inspect` vs `--inspect-brk`.** `--inspect` starts the inspector but doesn't pause; your script races past your first breakpoint if you attach too late. Use `--inspect-brk` when you need to set br
STEP|13|**Port collisions.** Default is `9229`. If multiple Node processes are inspecting, pass `--inspect=0` (random port) and read the actual URL from `/json/list`:
STEP|14|**Child processes.** `--inspect` on a parent does NOT inspect its children. Use `NODE_OPTIONS='--inspect-brk' node parent.js` to propagate to every child; be aware they all need unique ports (Node aut
STEP|15|**Background kills.** If you `Ctrl+C` out of `node inspect` while the target is paused, the target stays paused. Either `cont` first, or `kill` the target explicitly.
STEP|16|**Running `node inspect` through an agent terminal.** It's a PTY-friendly REPL. In Hermes, launch it with `terminal(pty=true)` or `background=true` + `process(action='submit', data='...')`. Non-PTY fo
STEP|17|**Security.** `--inspect=0.0.0.0:9229` exposes arbitrary code execution. Always bind to `127.0.0.1` (the default) unless you have an isolated network.
STEP|18|[ ] `curl -s http://127.0.0.1:9229/json/list` returns exactly the target you expect
STEP|19|[ ] First breakpoint actually hits (if it doesn't, you likely missed `--inspect-brk` or attached after execution completed)
STEP|20|[ ] Source listing at pause shows the right file (mismatch = sourcemap issue, see pitfall 1)
STEP|21|[ ] `exec process.pid` in `repl` returns the PID you meant to attach to
STEP|22|"Why is this variable undefined at line X?"**
STEP|23|"What's the call path into this function?"**
STEP|24|"This async chain hangs — where?"**
